<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9070&amp;p=97387#p97387</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9070&amp;p=97387#p97387"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[BASIC coding app for DSi/3DS coming this summer to NA]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9070&amp;p=97387#p97387"><![CDATA[
The main problem is having to type all your code on a tiny touchscreen and not being able to directly import graphics from standard formats.  This solves that and that's really enough.<br /><br />You're not going to see an open source clone that works on regular PCs.  You'd basically have to write a DS emulator to get it to work to the exact same spec, since some included commands seem to clearly use DS's built-in sprite scaling/rotation/collision capabilities, with whatever unique quirks they might have.  You also need to extract the program's included audio samples for its ~127 instruments and at least as many sound effects.  If you really want to be thorough, you also have to reverse engineer or license the speech synthesis tech used in the Japanese version.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3438">UncleSporky</a> — Wed Aug 01, 2012 8:44 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
